Salem man accused of sex crimes in Linn County

  • Nov 22, 2019
  • Nov 22, 2019 Updated Jan 2, 2020
  • 0
  • Facebook
  • Twitter
  • WhatsApp
  • SMS
  • Email
  • Print
  • Save

A Salem man was indicted on several sex crimes charges during an arraignment in Linn County Circuit Court on Friday afternoon.

Adam Scot Liechty, 26, was accused of first-degree unlawful sexual penetration and five counts of first-degree sex abuse.

Prosecutor Conor McCahill requested $300,000 bail for Liechty, who appeared via teleconference from the Linn County Jail. McCahill added that the accuser in the case is an elementary school-aged girl.

“These charges are all presumptive prison. These are all Measure 11,” he said. Measure 11 is an Oregon law that requires mandatory minimum sentences of several years in prison for the most serious crimes.

Defense attorney Ed Talmadge requested $50,000 security, the minimum for any Measure 11 offense.

Judge DeAnn Novotny set Liechty’s bail at $200,000.

The crimes allegedly occurred between January 2017 and February 2019.

The next hearing in the case was scheduled for Dec. 9.
